Unexplained deaths, pigs - Nigeria (Ibadan): RFI 20010810.1894
[1
Date: Sat 11 Aug 2001 12:08:59 +0200
From: Yves Leforban <Yves.Leforban@fao.org> [edited

The disease described by Dr B.O. Olugasa of the Dept of Vet Public Health
and Preventive Medicine, University of Ibadan, may be identical to a
disease that caused a series of mortalities in a nucleus pig farm in
Bingerville and other farms in the region, Cote d'Ivoire in 1992-1993. We
suspected Encephalomyocarditis Virus (EMCV) as the cause of the disease and
we confirmed it by virus isolation and serology. Evidence of virus
circulation was also detected in rodents. Only 6 of 34 sera collected in
the _Rattus rattus_ species trapped in Daloa area were found positive with
titre higher than 80; all sera collected in other species were found
negative with a titre lower than 10.
References:
Achaet Szifres: 1989 Encephalomycardite,in Zoonoses OIE.
Hubbard GB, Soike KF, Butler TM, Carey KD, Davis H, Butcher WI, Gauntt
CJ:1992 An encephalomyocarditis virus epizootic in a baboon colony.
Laboratory Animal Science 42:3 233-239
Joo HS 1992 Encephalomyocarditis Virus,in Diseases of Swine 7th edition
17:257-262
Kim S-H, Joo HS, Bergeland ME 1989 Serologic, virologic, and
histolopathologic observations of encephalomyocarditis virus infection in
mummified and stillborn pigs, J. Vet Diagn Invest 1:101-104
Koenen F, De Clercq K, Lefebvre J, Strobbe R 1994 Reproductive failure in
sows following experimental infection with a Belgian EMCV isolate.
Veterinary Microbiology 39:111-116
Paschaleri-Papadopoulou E, Axiotis I, Laspidis C 1990 Encephalomyocarditis
of Swine in Greece, Veterinary Record 126:364-365
Smith KE, Zimmerman J, Beran GW, Hill HT 1992 A Serosurvey of swine and
free-living species on Iowa farms for antibodies against
encephalomyocarditis virus. Can Vet J. 33:645-649
Williams MC:1981 Encephalomyocarditis virus infection. J.S.Afr.Vet.Assoc.
52:16
--
Yves Leforban
AGAH, FAO
Rome
<Yves.Leforban@fao.org>
